Location: Main Roped Climbing Wall > Alapocas Run State Park > Delaware
Description: The natural warmup boulder traverse a foot above ground level, on the vertical face between Arena Arete and Chossy's Corner. It's on par with, or a hair harder than, Arena Arete. Move delicately between little flakes at various heights and angles, a good drill for face climbing.

Location: Main Roped Climbing Wall > Alapocas Run State Park > Delaware
Description: Excellent tiny feet and almost impossible hands make this a really fun climb / boulder problem... for delaware...

Location: Main Roped Climbing Wall > Alapocas Run State Park > Delaware
Description: A former sport climb (rest in peace, homie). A short, crimpy, technical slab. Follow the two chopped bolts in the "groove" between two inward facing cuts in the rock. Balancey moves to a short crimpy crux followed by three possible finishes and counting... a dyno (most common way), some delicate foot moves and some features out to the left, and the static direct way with layback moves on bad crimps and bad feet. All three feel about the same difficulty to me but I'm 6ft so ymmv. More opinions on grade needed, I included the grade from the guide

Location: Heat Index Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Climb the tall face straight up, skirting right towards the top. Don't Fall.

Location: Heat Index Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Climb straight up the 2 tiered face.

Location: Heat Index Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Climb up onto the ledge and then take the inside corner and crack straight up.

Location: Heat Index Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Back and foot pressure traverse out to overhang. Pull the overhang and finish up the face.

Location: Heat Index Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Climb the slab, left and right aretes are off.

Location: Heat Index Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Short mantle problem.

Start all the way back underneath the left arete of "Hostage" [V3] with hands underclung on the left arete and feet on the boulder to the left of hostage. Bump hands along the edge and keep tension through the feet to work your way out from under the overhang. Once out from under you can use a layback approach or sink really good kneebars in between the boulders to work your hands farther up the arete. Top out on top of the boulder to the left of "Hostage".
Climb the left side of the tall slab to the right of Winter Seasoning. Arete is on. Best not to fall once committed. A TR can be set up with trad gear if you are so inclined.

Start on top of the block that Hostage, and Starr Report are on. Climb the left side of the knobby slab using the crack and face holds. Do not fall. A TR can be set up with trad gear if you are so inclined.

Start on the right side of the slab above Hostage and The Starr Report. Use cracks, the arete, and concerning sandy feet to climb up. Do not fall. A TR can be set up with trad gear if you are so inclined.
Sit start with hands in the left facing crack. Pull up to small but positive holds and continue up trending slightly right.
Start on good left edge and low side-pull right with good feet. Arete is off. Move up the face.

Start with smeary feet and lay back tension on right facing corner (block underneath and to the right are off). Follow corner up to a good edge and then get high feet to step up to a steep rail. Top out.

Start hanging on the obvious jug about 6ft off the ground with feet on a good wide edge underneath. Deadpoint up. Reach up for a juggy side-pull and adjust feet to catch a good rest if you need it. Play with feet and balance to be able to make crux moves to the lip.

Stand start left hand on sloper at head height, right hand on large undercling and paste a foot or two on. Fire to ledge(crux) then continue up arete and top out straight above. Clean fall zone. (lose large block to left off)
Start with right hand undercling and left on the lip. Use heel hook and follow slopers up to sharp right hold around the corner to gain the arete to an easier top out.
Start on hostage (obvious jug in the middle of the boulder) and traverse the lip to the right into Over the Hump day. New favorite line in the area.
Start on double undercling and bad feet then move up on small edges and crimps to jug finish. Dyno at any point for the same grade.
Easiest route on the spacklehead boulder and the best way to get off of the top.

Beta break for spacklehead. Probably worth considering it as it’s own proboem. Sit start with easy feet and some fun, straightforward dynamic movement or alternatively some reachy, schisty static moves. Use the arete out to the left and an undercling to the right

Start on the lower left edge of the seam on the back, slightly overhanging face on the backside or the spacklehead boulder. Move up and slightly right on the face using small crimps and edges, top out. Stay on the face, right arete is off. No harder than V3 with good beta. Consider giving the crimps a brush, it makes a difference.
Start on the right side arete of the backside overhanging face of the spacklehead boulder. Follow the arete to the top trending slightly right to finish, and top out.
Start as for spacklehead but follow the seam up and right around the corner to the slabby featured face and follow the features up to top out.

The start is only PG-13 if you don't have a spotter and the difficulty is above your pay grade. The start is on the overhanging blocky backside of the spacklehead boulder facing the river. Start with a juggy looking but just ok undercling for a left hand and a juggy full right hand pocket. Use a couple burly moves to go out left and eventually reach the crack that begins in the upper left of the alcove. Follow this crack and easy climbing to the top of the boulder. For a spicy R-rated finish (still easy though), once you turn the corner left onto the face, follow good holds up the arete until it slopes out then trend left for the last couple feet.
Sit start in the center of the face with low right sidepull and higher left hand. Move directly up the face to top out finish same as Spacklehead.

Location: Black Widow Boulder > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: An easy up or down climb.  Great for warmup or if you’re scrambling the hill to Spearhead.  Left hand reaches up to any ledge.  Right hand on the 3” crystal hold below eye-level.  Feet are whatever you want.  High-step up with right foot onto the 3” crystal.  Work up above the crack, then another move or two to send.

Location: Black Widow Boulder > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Start with your left foot in the obvious cutout (bottom center of photo).  Right foot can match, smear, or rest on any feature.  Hands on face or in a crack.  High-step right foot up to a shallow ledge.  Balance, step up, and insert left foot into the large crack.  Match feet.  Work up the face using cracks and dishes.  The arete on the left of the upper face is off.

Location: Black Widow Boulder > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Short but very stout. Start with hands on the bottom of the steeply slanting rail in the middle of the boulder and feet deep underneath on a good edge. Do a lot of twisting and turning and squeezing to follow the steep rail to the top. Good holds, but harder than it looks.

Route: The Devil Is In The Details
Location: Black Widow Boulder > Rockford Park > Delaware
Route name: The Devil Is In The Details
Description: Super awesome sustained problem with super specific sequencing through the crux. You can really only give it a few goes before the tops of your feet and shins are too tired to keep you off the ground.

Location: Scattered Small Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Sit start with smeary feet and a good flat hand hold. Follow obvious holds straight up.

Location: Scattered Small Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Start with wide hands and feet on blocks below. Use the crack and potentially a tight fingerlock to stand up on the face. Topout up and left. Currently there is a terrifyingly large fallen tree overtop of this, but it doesnt stop you from toppoing out. Climb at your own discretion.Have a strong spotter to keep you from tumbling off the small landing pedestal.

Location: Scattered Small Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Use large holds and smeary feet to climb the short corner.

Location: Scattered Small Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: The low sit start to Backboard [V0]. Start in wide compression on both corners, smearing feet to stay on. Slap your way into a more secure stance and climb up.

Location: Scattered Small Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Sit-start compressing both arete, with creative feet. Do a couple bumps up the corners until you get a good hold over the top of the lip. Follow good holds up and right until you can top out.

Location: Scattered Small Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Start with hands on the incut dimple at the lip of the overhang and/or on the right arete. All surrounding blocks are off. Get a high smeary foot onto the lip and use a devilish sidepull to work up to a positive flake far  up the face. Be gentle with the flake, I don't fully trust its integrity.

Location: Scattered Small Boulders > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Start left hand on the slopey rail and right hand on a small crimp on the face. Move out left for a couple moves, then back right for a tricky mantle over the lip to top out. Topping out left is easier (v3) and up the middle will likely be the hardest, but is still a project.

Location: Makeout Cave Cluster > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Start on the jug edge deep underneath the tree. Follow jugs up and out right of the tree.

Location: Makeout Cave Cluster > Rockford Park > Delaware
Description: Start on the boulders underneath the cap. Use holds in the corner and very awkward movement to grunt onto the slab and tenuously step up to top out.
Follow slab closest to corner up to top.
SDS with right hand on undercling and left hand fingerlocked in crack. Climb straight up following crimps to the top out.
Start as for Corporate Blues, but follow seam right, avoiding jugs on upper face. Finish around corner.
SDS by laybacking on crack. Bump up along middle seam. Continue along back edge to finish.
On the left side of boulder, follow the arete to the top. Start with right hand on the arete and left hand on crimp on the face of the climb.
Start with left hand undercling on arete, and left hand on good blocky hold. Go straight up.
Start on the same jug as flex-a-flake, but go up and right for crimp jugs above the lip. Topout. More precise than hard.

This problem is a variation/extension to "roughed the butt". After making the first move on roughed the butt, do not keep climbing up. Instead follow the sharp crystal lined crack to the right as far as you can, and then top out.
Start matched on the large left facing jug flake with feet underneath, adjust hands if needed and throw up and left for a hold then for the flexing flake. Continue straight up.

A very low sit start to either Flex-a-flake or Roughed the Butt. Start with a left hand side pull and right hand under cling paired with some knee bar shenanigans. Pull up in a lot of tension and throw for the jug flake. Finished as for either problem.

The crux is the middle of the face, the crack gets pretty shallow.  Other than that the rock has a great texture and the cracks are decent size.  Good for learning to smear or warmup for bigger climbs.

Location: Front and Center Boulder > Brandywine Park > Delaware
Description: Start in the very venter of the boulder with hands underclinging in the crack and some awkward feet. Use some rounded but good crimps to pull up and reach for the jug flake. Don't take the topout for granted.

Location: Front and Center Boulder > Brandywine Park > Delaware
Description: Sit Start with hands on the good blocky ledge. Go straight up using a crimp on the face and the corners. The big juggy block way to the left is off. Not quite as straightforward as it looks.

Location: Front and Center Boulder > Brandywine Park > Delaware
Description: Sit start hanging on the good blocky edge below the inside corner. Use some trickery to climb up and into the corner and then topout. Will seem much harder without good beta.
